\section{Introduction}
\label{sec:intro}
%══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

The SR companion set established the classical-force sector of CPP from
a scalar SSV broadcast: $|\SSV|_{\rm abs}$ propagates at speed $c$ via
12-neighbor shell broadcast, giving $1/r^2$ force laws, and the PSR
formula $\PSR_{\rm eff} = \lP/(1+k\cdot\Delta|\SSV|_{\rm abs})$ recovers
all special-relativistic effects.  The Newtonian Gravity companion showed
that mass-energy sources compressive SSV, with $G = \hbar c/\mP^2$
(Newtonian Gravity companion, \S3).

However, the scalar broadcast is incomplete for general relativity.  The
Schwarzschild metric requires two independent metric perturbations of
equal magnitude:
\begin{equation}
  g_{tt} \;=\; 1 - \frac{2GM}{rc^2},
  \qquad
  g_{rr} \;=\; \left(1 - \frac{2GM}{rc^2}\right)^{-1}
  \approx 1 + \frac{2GM}{rc^2}.
  \label{eq:Schwarzschild_weak}
\end{equation}
The scalar $|\SSV|_{\rm abs}$ accounts for $g_{tt}$ (time dilation)
but not $g_{rr}$ (spatial curvature).  The net SSV vector
$\mathbf{\SSV}_{\rm net}$ provides the missing component.

The extended Lattice State Packet carries four components:
\begin{equation}
  \LSP \;=\; \bigl(\mathbf{x}_{\rm GP},\; t_{\rm abs},\;
  |\SSV|_{\rm abs},\; \mathbf{\SSV}_{\rm net}\bigr).
  \label{eq:LSP}
\end{equation}

\begin{remark}[Backward compatibility]
In flat space, $\mathbf{\SSV}_{\rm net}$ averages to zero over the
isotropic DP sea.  The extended LSP reduces to the SR-era scalar-only
broadcast in flat spacetime, and all SR results are recovered unchanged.
\end{remark}

Three rigorous claims:
\begin{itemize}[noitemsep]
  \item The extended LSP is constructed from $E_{\rm pol} = mc^2$,
    not postulated independently.
  \item Shell broadcast of both components reproduces the weak-field
    Schwarzschild metric, the factor-of-two lensing result, geodesic
    motion, and the equivalence principle.
  \item $Z_0$, $\mu_0$, and $\epsilon_0$ are derived from lattice
    parameters.
\end{itemize}
Full Einstein equations and strong-field solutions are deferred.

