\section{Effective Horizon and the GP Exclusion Rule}
\label{sec:BH}
%══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

The Schwarzschild radius $r_s = 2GM/c^2$ marks where $g_{tt} \to 0$
in Eq.~\eqref{eq:Schwarzschild_CPP}.  In CPP terms, at $r = r_s$:
\begin{equation}
  k\,\Delta|\SSV|_{\rm abs}(r_s) \;=\; 1
  \quad\Rightarrow\quad
  \PSR_{\rm eff}(r_s) \;=\; \frac{\lP}{2}.
  \label{eq:horizon}
\end{equation}
The PSR has contracted to half its vacuum value.  This is the \emph{effective
horizon}: the PSR formula predicts that CPs inside $r_s$ have their
spatial budget fully consumed by gravitational SSV, preventing escape.

The CP Exclusion Rule (one CP per GP per tick; Absolute Moment companion,
\S2) prevents a true singularity at $r = 0$: as the PSR contracts toward
$\lP/2$, GPs become unavailable as destinations for infalling CPs, which
are deflected to neighboring GPs.  Black holes in CPP are therefore
layered structures of maximum-density CP configurations rather than
mathematical singularities --- consistent with the GP Exclusion
mechanism that drives Big Bang expansion (see §\ref{sec:open},
open problem 4).

\begin{remark}[Planck-scale cutoff]
At $\Delta\SSV = \SSV_{\rm crit}$ (the PSR saturation point from
Version~16), the PSR reaches its minimum $\lP/2$ and no further
contraction occurs.  This natural ultraviolet cutoff at the Planck scale
is a CPP prediction that differs from classical GR and may resolve the
information paradox without invoking quantum gravity beyond what CPP
already provides.
\end{remark}

